snippet.textDisplay: There are a lot of short tracks across America that have those little sweeper buggy things. If I re-call correctly, my Dad was telling me years ago that they originated at Florida racetracks like New Smyrna, and then started become a bit more common place throughout the east coast. Some of them have faded away however. Holland Speedway in NY has had one for many years however, and it was always the coolest thing growing up, but that's all it was ever really used for. Cleaning up fluid on the racetrack. Never a pace car nor for fire rescues. Leave the pacing to a proper car, and fire rescue to the firefighters on hand / guys rushing over on ATVs.

snippet.textDisplay:
Hey Cleetus, i used to spend every saturday at Desoto back in the day. Was a friend of the owner as well. I reached out to you on Facebook but you must have missed it.


Just a little insight about the buggy (haven't watched the video fully as of now):
That thing always ran like crap, it had a broom with it that was below your feet that you could drop and sweep the track, though it added so much drag it'd stall the buggy out if you tried to use it. Thats probably why its gone, come to think of it... Even without the broom it'd stall on track all the time though.


Anyways, you have the full support of manatee county in bringing back a local past time! I hope you do great things with it, and if you're looking for work when hosting public events I would love to help you out. Big fan of what you do, been watching for a long time, and seeing you buy up Desoto raised my respect for you a whole hell of a lot.


EDIT: The broom used to be way bigger, just saw it.

snippet.textDisplay: You have not spent any time at a race track at all. I suggest you stop at a local track for a couple hours. That VW powered sweeper is a great piece of gear. as a race goes on, there are crashes and oil leaks, they need to be swept up quickly as the race cars are still on the track. The spectators (that pay to see a race) don't want to wait all night to see an oil spill cleaned up. The competitors don't want to drive into an oily track to crash into the wall with a 50,000 race car. At a good track (I bet that was one ) the crash is towed away and the oil or coolant cleaned up and the race is restarted in only a few laps of caution. Ala the slide back truck. During the race it is very possible to send the ambulance off to the hospital, Hopefully the track has two. I wish you luck with this track and hope you find a good promoter to run it for you.
